rilla army into a modern fighting force capable of bringing down the formidable French army.Taking readers from the outbreak of fighting in 1945 to the epic battle at Dien Bien Phu, Christopher Goscha shows how Ho transformed Vietnam from a decentralized guerrilla state based in the countryside to a single-party communist state shaped by a specific form of “War Communism.” Goscha discusses how the Vietnamese operated both states through economics, trade, policing, information gathering, and communications technology. He challenges the wisdom of counterinsurgency methods developed by the French and still used by the Americans today, and explains why the First Indochina War was arguably the most brutal war of decolonization in the twentieth century, killing a million Vietnamese, most of them civilians.Panoramic in scope, The Road to Dien Bien Phu transforms our understanding of this conflict and the one the United States would later enter, and sheds new light on communist warfare and statecraft in East Asia today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunismzVietnamxHistoryy20th century. 0aDecolonizationzVietnamxHistory. 0aIndochinese War, 1946-1954. 7aHISTORY / Military / Vietnam War.2bisacsh  a320th Division (Vietnam).  aArtillery.  aB?o Ð?i.  aBangkok.  aBattle of Cao Bang (1979).  aBattle of Dien Bien Phu.  aBattle of Hanoi.  aBlockade.  aBranch Office.  aCambodia.  aCentral Vietnam.  aChiang Kai-shek.  aCommunism.  aCounter-insurgency.  aDecolonization.  aFirst Indochina War.  aFrench Colonial.  aFrench Indochina.  aFront organization.  aHainan.  aHaiphong.  aHanoi.  aHo Chi Minh trail.  aHo Chi Minh.  aHoang Van Chi.  aIndochina Wars.  aIndochina.  aKuomintang.  aLaos.  aLe Monde.  aLuang Prabang.  aLê Ð?c Th?.  aMao Zedong.  aMekong Delta.